{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480052"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"7"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/7"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.03,0.19,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103527"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"7"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"86"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41953"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103527"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old retired woman presents to a Rural Emergency Department with acute abdominal pain and wound dehiscence from a recent midline abdominal surgical scar. She states she has undergone multiple surgical procedures for Crohn\u0027s disease in various leading centres in the United States, and has attended your hospital due to the good reputation of the surgical department. She is vague and inconsistent about the specific details of her prior treatment. She has with her a discharge summary from her most recent surgical procedure that outlines a presentation with abdominal pain, but no identifiably active Crohn\u0027s disease identified on surgical exploration. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Closer inspection of the wound reveals some of the sutures in situ appear to have been cleanly cut at the point of the dehiscence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factitious disorder","Conversion disorder","Malingering","Illness anxiety disorder","Somatic symptom disorder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactitious disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It involves the falsification of physical or psychological signs or symptoms, or induction of injury or disease associated with identified deception. The patient\u0027s vague and inconsistent history, along with the cleanly cut sutures, suggest deliberate feigning of illness. Importantly, in factitious disorder, the apparent aim is to assume the sick role (primary gain), in the absence of obvious external rewards. This disorder embodies persistent problems related to illness perception and identity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (functional neurological symptom disorder) presents with one or more symptoms of altered voluntary motor or sensory function, i.e., neurological symptoms. There must be clinical findings that show clear evidence of incompatibility with neurological disease. This doesn\u0027t fit the patient\u0027s presentation of abdominal pain and wound dehiscence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalingering\u003C/strong\u003E is differentiated from factitious disorder by the intentional reporting of symptoms for personal gain or secondary gain (e.g., money, time off work). There\u0027s no evidence of external incentives in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIllness anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E, previously known as hypochondriasis, is characterized by preoccupation with having or acquiring a serious illness. This patient\u0027s presentation involves actual physical symptoms and apparent self-harm, which goes beyond mere anxiety about illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomatic symptom disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves positive symptoms and signs PLUS abnormal thoughts, feelings, and behaviors in response to these symptoms. While this could be considered, the evidence of deliberate deception (cut sutures) makes factitious disorder more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Factitious disorder involves deliberate deception or feigning of illness, but not for personal gain.","Factitious disorder is characterized by persistent problems related to illness perception and identity."],"references":["Bass C, Wade DT. Malingering and factitious disorder. Pract Neurol 2019; 19:96-105.","DSM V"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"7"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T13:11:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T13:11:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103527"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms